WRITING.TEXT: I #8217;m not sure but I can give you a little slice of where ALP lost it for the people in my friendship group. We are all around 30 and live in Melbourne. Most of us agreed with the vast majority of ALP policies, apart from negative gearing and capital gains tax policies. Pretty much all of us said the same thing, if it wasn #8217;t for those 2 things we would be voting labor. The problem was that most of us have a home or an investment property (whilst renting where we want to live) with plans to hopefully buy another in the future or really just have options with our existing properties. The possibilities of losing those options and even the possibility of rent increases for those of us renting basically swung the majority of people in our group. We #8217;re not backwards Queenslanders, we #8217;re not racist bigots, we #8217;re not religious nutters. We believe in climate change (some of us very strongly), 2 of us are teachers and 3 of us are even construction workers in the union. But those policies are what swung us away from labor.

That #8217;s the reality of the situation. Mind you I wouldn #8217;t say we are all wealthy. None of us have more than one property, some of us live in that house or rent it out and rent somewhere else our selves. We all worked hard, saved, some of us started business and only now are most of us starting to earn above average full time wage. Many of us didn #8217;t want to risk further house price falls due to policy (some only bought recently and their houses are now already worth less). Some were worried about rents increasing and yes others who maybe were already planning to buy another property in the next few years just didn #8217;t want to loose thousands a year not being able to claim expenses (which you can do on any other investment). Also if they ever want to sell an investment it will have cost them probably tens of thousands. We all basically have a vision that we don #8217;t want to have to rely on the pension or an ever dwindling superfund. Property has been a good stable way to do that for generations. They went big and underestimated how many people care about their own finances and future financial ambitions. Especially when people have legitimately worked hard, been frugal and saved for years to buy a house. I #8217;m not here to judge (tbh I donkeyed because I was so torn) I #8217;m just answering the question as to what I saw failed with labor.

WRITING.TITLE: Texas really isn #8217;t that big!
WRITING.TEXT: Every American goes on about how big Texas is, yeh maybe in comparison to other US states or countries in Europe but the world is a much bigger place. I mean it #8217;s not even America #8217;s largest state (that would be Alaska which is over double the size). I #8217;m Australian and laugh at reading or hearing about how long it takes to drive across it (obligatory #8216;you can drive all day and still be in the same state #8217;). Texas is smaller than 5 out of the 7 states and territories we have and by a fare long shot as well, I mean WA is over 3 times larger. Do you know where Texas rates in size among the world #8217;s state and territory sizes? 26th! I #8217;m sorry Americans it #8217;s just not that big a place.

I don #8217;t see what population has to do with anything. If it does then I think China would like to have a word. And you #8217;re highlighting precisely my point, the world is bigger than the US and Europe. Some perspective would be good. It #8217;s got nothing to do with Australia, just using it as my personal example. Russia has the largest state but closer to home for Americans, Canada has states larger than Texas.
High on the list maybe but in actual area size not really.

Earth and Saturn are planets, when you compare Earth to every other planet we know about in our milky way then no we #8217;re not very big. Just like when you compare Texas to other states or territories around the world it #8217;s not very big. Let me put it this way if you put it on a scale of 1 to 10 with the smallest state in the world (by km2) being a 1 and the largest in the world being a 10 Texas is about a 2.
It #8217;s not that big and I never said it was. Although Australia is a fair bit closer to being the largest country in the world than Texas is to being the largest state in the world.

I don #8217;t really think that #8217;s how comparisons work. Everything is relative. A baby elephant is small compared to an adult elephant but still massive compared to a mouse. This is about comparing apples with apples or in this case states and states. The Texas is a large US state, it #8217;s not that big compared to the world #8217;s biggest states. It being big is your perspective. To someone living in a large Russian state or in Western Australia it would be small. To get rid of the perspectives compare it to everything in that category. Texas is about 1/5th the size of the worlds largest state or territory, It ranks high but in pure size terms it #8217;s much closer to the smallest states in the world than to the largest.

WRITING.TEXT: No. Holden held a very special place in a lot of Australians. It was our car, especially the commodore, which from 2006 onwards was completely designed and engineered here (apart from the V8s engines). Most Australians grew up with a Holden commodore (or ford falcon) as their family car. Holden was the number one selling car brand here for many decades, up until 2010. It #8217;s sort of bittersweet because once they stopping making Holdens here and started wholly importing inferior products their sales slumped massively. It needed to happen but it #8217;s still sad.
Also warranties must still be legally upheld. Spare parts and service centres will still be around for 10 years. [Holden Warranty](https://www.google.com.au/amp/amp.abc.net.au/article/11972296)
I dunno the VF series 2 SS redlines were a really good car. And the last of the HSVs were also awesome.

While I agree that it definitely was a marketing issue that sunk them, the cars they were importing were nothing special and although the commodore and astra were good and drove better than most of the competition, they were not segment leading. The ZB, why would you buy it over mazda 6 or VW passat? The Arcadia? Plenty of better SUV competition from other brands. Even the Colorado, why buy one over a Ford Ranger or Amarok. The cars they were importing felt cheap inside and out and I don #8217;t think appealed to buyers, they certainly didn #8217;t to me.
